00:04:08.916 --> 00:04:11.486
Because every AR app needs to --

00:04:11.786 --> 00:04:13.376
needs that understanding in

00:04:13.376 --> 00:04:14.666
order to place its objects into

00:04:14.666 --> 00:04:16.446
the world, or show the user that

00:04:16.446 --> 00:04:17.196
information.

00:04:17.616 --> 00:04:20.266
And, the way ARKit builds that

00:04:20.266 --> 00:04:22.065
understanding of the world, is

00:04:22.065 --> 00:04:23.116
by getting you to move your

00:04:23.116 --> 00:04:24.816
device, by having you move

00:04:24.816 --> 00:04:25.186
around.

00:04:25.186 --> 00:04:27.076
And, that's a little bit

00:04:27.076 --> 00:04:29.346
different from other places that

00:04:29.346 --> 00:04:30.846
you might have looked through a

00:04:30.846 --> 00:04:32.456
device, seen a camera preview,

00:04:32.646 --> 00:04:33.596
in the past.

00:04:34.386 --> 00:04:35.386
Like, for example, when you're

00:04:35.386 --> 00:04:37.096
taking a photo, you just need to

00:04:37.096 --> 00:04:38.836
point the device where you want

00:04:38.836 --> 00:04:39.636
to frame the shot.

00:04:40.376 --> 00:04:42.066
But, in AR, you really do need

00:04:42.066 --> 00:04:43.576
to start moving, looking at the

00:04:43.576 --> 00:04:44.916
same place from different

00:04:44.916 --> 00:04:46.466
positions, and looking at it

00:04:46.466 --> 00:04:47.446
from some different angles.

00:04:47.956 --> 00:04:51.056
So, the trick here is to let

00:04:51.056 --> 00:04:52.746
