00:04:52.746 --> 00:04:52.916
do.

00:04:52.916 --> 00:04:54.476
Let them know how to move, that

00:04:54.476 --> 00:04:55.426
they need to move their device.

00:04:55.426 --> 00:04:57.416
And, the way to do that is to

00:04:57.416 --> 00:04:58.826
give them a fixed reference.

00:04:59.096 --> 00:05:00.266
Give them something to base that

00:05:00.266 --> 00:05:01.296
understanding off of.

00:05:02.346 --> 00:05:03.416
And, let's talk about that.

00:05:03.416 --> 00:05:04.606
Let's take a look at an example.

00:05:05.676 --> 00:05:07.236
So, this is the game Euclidean

00:05:07.236 --> 00:05:07.756
Lands.

00:05:08.256 --> 00:05:09.546
And, what it's showing here, is

00:05:09.546 --> 00:05:11.356
the device moving around inside

00:05:11.356 --> 00:05:11.986
of a room.

00:05:12.846 --> 00:05:13.936
And, that's really great,

00:05:13.936 --> 00:05:15.376
because you can see here,

00:05:15.376 --> 00:05:18.026
without any text exactly what it

00:05:18.026 --> 00:05:19.866
is you need to do, that you need

00:05:19.866 --> 00:05:21.366
to move the device within that

00:05:21.366 --> 00:05:24.596
room, and just turning the

00:05:24.596 --> 00:05:25.666
device to look at a different

00:05:25.666 --> 00:05:27.496
angle isn't going to be enough.

00:05:28.056 --> 00:05:29.406
So, without any text, it's

00:05:29.406 --> 00:05:31.156
really clear from that fixed

00:05:31.156 --> 00:05:32.976
reference of the room, exactly

00:05:32.976 --> 00:05:35.346
what you need to do.

00:05:35.476 --> 00:05:37.426
And, usually, most of the time,

00:05:37.596 --> 00:05:38.606
that is all you're going to

00:05:38.606 --> 00:05:38.976
need.

00:05:39.546 --> 00:05:41.396
ARKit is even faster to build

00:05:41.396 --> 00:05:42.746
that understanding of the world

00:05:43.106 --> 00:05:44.096
in iOS 12.

00:05:44.696 --> 00:05:47.136
So, in even more cases that is

00:05:47.136 --> 00:05:48.316
all you're going to need.

00:05:48.676 --> 00:05:49.956
You just need to start moving,

00:05:49.956 --> 00:05:51.036
and you're ready to go.

00:05:52.416 --> 00:05:54.056
But, of course, there are some

00:05:54.056 --> 00:05:55.646
situations that aren't quite as

00:05:55.646 --> 00:05:56.636
well suited to AR.

00:05:57.256 --> 00:05:58.836
Maybe you're in a dark room, or

00:05:58.986 --> 00:06:00.696
it's really reflective, and it's

00:06:00.696 --> 00:06:04.026
not as easy to -- for ARKit to

00:06:04.026 --> 00:06:04.796
start building that

00:06:04.796 --> 00:06:05.606
understanding.

00:06:05.806 --> 00:06:07.606
So, it can take ARKit a little

00:06:07.606 --> 00:06:09.306
bit of time to get ready.

00:06:09.676 --> 00:06:11.346
It might not happen immediately.

00:06:12.616 --> 00:06:14.126
And, in those situations, if

00:06:14.126 --> 00:06:15.236
you're still being told to move

00:06:15.236 --> 00:06:16.526
your device, you're still

00:06:16.526 --> 00:06:17.506
looking at something that says

00:06:17.506 --> 00:06:19.336
to you, move your device around,

00:06:19.796 --> 00:06:20.966
people might start to wonder,

00:06:21.416 --> 00:06:23.936
why is the app not working?

00:06:23.936 --> 00:06:25.356
Does the app not understand the

00:06:25.356 --> 00:06:26.436
movement that they're making?

00:06:26.806 --> 00:06:27.666
And, it might get -- start to

00:06:27.666 --> 00:06:28.566
get confusing.

00:06:29.376 --> 00:06:30.926
So, what you need is some kind

00:06:30.926 --> 00:06:32.796
of feedback that lets people

00:06:32.796 --> 00:06:34.156
know that they're not doing

00:06:34.156 --> 00:06:35.046
anything wrong.

00:06:35.196 --> 00:06:36.366
They're doing exactly what they

00:06:36.366 --> 00:06:38.316
should be doing to get into AR.

00:06:38.706 --> 00:06:39.916
And, they should just keep doing

00:06:39.916 --> 00:06:40.066
it.

00:06:40.246 --> 00:06:41.556
So, let's take a look at an

00:06:41.556 --> 00:06:41.976
example.

00:06:46.266 --> 00:06:48.146
So, this is how iOS 12's

00:06:48.256 --> 00:06:50.426
built-in AR apps help guide

00:06:50.426 --> 00:06:51.446
people into AR.

00:06:52.176 --> 00:06:53.486
You can see the device moving

00:06:53.486 --> 00:06:55.586
over the fixed reference of that

00:06:55.586 --> 00:06:57.346
surface, by showing you that you

00:06:57.346 --> 00:06:58.206
need to move it.

00:06:58.356 --> 00:06:59.456
You can't just keep it in one

00:06:59.456 --> 00:07:00.576
place, or rotate it.

00:07:01.466 --> 00:07:04.036
And then, once you've started

00:07:04.036 --> 00:07:06.056
moving the device, the surface

00:07:06.056 --> 00:07:07.616
transitions into a cube.

00:07:07.866 --> 00:07:10.806
And, that cube spins with the

00:07:10.806 --> 00:07:12.206
movement of the device, giving

00:07:12.206 --> 00:07:13.666
you real, connected, direct

00:07:13.666 --> 00:07:15.196
feedback that you're on the

00:07:15.196 --> 00:07:16.916
right path, and you're doing the

00:07:16.916 --> 00:07:17.506
right thing.

00:07:18.696 --> 00:07:20.276
And then, once ARKit has built

00:07:20.276 --> 00:07:21.406
that understanding, it's all

00:07:21.406 --> 00:07:23.946
ready, the cube spins away, and

00:07:23.946 --> 00:07:25.516
you're ready to go in your AR

00:07:25.516 --> 00:07:25.966
experience.

00:07:29.266 --> 00:07:30.896
So, that's how the built-in apps

00:07:30.896 --> 00:07:33.256
in iOS 12 help guide people into

00:07:33.256 --> 00:07:33.526
AR.

00:07:33.996 --> 00:07:35.276
And, your apps should follow

00:07:35.276 --> 00:07:36.446
those same principles.

00:07:36.876 --> 00:07:38.636
They should help people know

00:07:38.636 --> 00:07:39.476
that they need to move their

00:07:39.476 --> 00:07:41.016
device, and give them that

00:07:41.016 --> 00:07:42.126
feedback that they're doing the

00:07:42.126 --> 00:07:42.806
right thing.

00:07:43.296 --> 00:07:44.586
But, your apps don't need to

00:07:44.586 --> 00:07:45.786
follow that same style.

00:07:45.786 --> 00:07:46.666
They don't need to look like

00:07:46.666 --> 00:07:48.066
line drawings.

00:07:48.066 --> 00:07:48.886
AR should feel like an

00:07:48.886 --> 00:07:50.306
integrated part of your app.

00:07:50.746 --> 00:07:52.406
It should feel native to your

00:07:52.406 --> 00:07:53.206
app's style.

00:07:53.206 --> 00:07:54.466
And, it shouldn't feel like

00:07:54.466 --> 00:07:56.256
something that's attached on, or

00:07:56.256 --> 00:07:58.026
this flow is something that's

00:07:58.026 --> 00:07:59.106
added on after the fact.

00:07:59.236 --> 00:08:01.186
So, the important part is to

00:08:01.186 --> 00:08:02.556
help people down the right path,

00:08:03.076 --> 00:08:04.136
but it should feel like part of

00:08:04.136 --> 00:08:05.386
your app while you're doing

00:08:05.386 --> 00:08:05.626
that.

00:08:06.146 --> 00:08:09.026
And, the last thing I want to

00:08:09.026 --> 00:08:10.446
talk about for helping get

00:08:10.446 --> 00:08:12.156
people into AR, is that it's

00:08:12.156 --> 00:08:14.676
important to balance your

00:08:14.676 --> 00:08:16.176
instructions, your guidance, how

00:08:16.176 --> 00:08:17.306
you're helping people get into

00:08:17.306 --> 00:08:19.216
AR with being really efficient

00:08:19.216 --> 00:08:20.646
when people already do know what

00:08:20.646 --> 00:08:21.906
to do.

00:08:22.016 --> 00:08:24.006
So, if somebody already knows

00:08:24.006 --> 00:08:25.156
