So, one of those options is to

00:09:23.306 --> 00:09:25.836
build an AR experience entirely

00:09:25.866 --> 00:09:26.886
in two dimensions.

00:09:27.456 --> 00:09:28.566
You don't need to show a camera

00:09:28.566 --> 00:09:29.246
preview.

00:09:29.406 --> 00:09:30.696
You don't need any kind of 3D

00:09:30.696 --> 00:09:31.376
graphics.

00:09:31.746 --> 00:09:33.276
You're using that information

00:09:33.516 --> 00:09:35.186
that ARKit gets about the world

00:09:35.646 --> 00:09:38.546
to present a great AR

00:09:38.546 --> 00:09:40.646
experiences entirely in 2D.

00:09:41.986 --> 00:09:42.676
So, let's take a look at an

00:09:42.676 --> 00:09:43.726
example of that.

00:09:44.666 --> 00:09:46.166
This is the game "Rainbrow."

00:09:47.026 --> 00:09:49.266
And, in Rainbrow, the way you

00:09:49.266 --> 00:09:50.396
control you character is by

00:09:50.396 --> 00:09:51.756
moving your eyebrows up and

00:09:51.756 --> 00:09:51.956
down.

00:09:52.516 --> 00:10:11.500
[ Game Music ]

00:10:15.516 --> 00:10:19.876
[ Applause ]

00:10:20.376 --> 00:10:22.466
So, there's no need of any kind

00:10:22.466 --> 00:10:23.546
of camera preview here.

00:10:23.776 --> 00:10:25.686
There's no need for any 3D

00:10:25.686 --> 00:10:26.216
graphics.

00:10:26.646 --> 00:10:28.396
It's a lot more fun entirely in

00:10:28.396 --> 00:10:30.736
2D, but it's still a great AR

00:10:30.736 --> 00:10:31.396
experience.

00:10:31.896 --> 00:10:34.976
So, that was AR in 2D.

00:10:35.556 --> 00:10:36.936
But, another way, another thing

00:10:36.936 --> 00:10:39.036
you can do with ARKit is you can

00:10:39.036 --> 00:10:40.066
build things that I would

00:10:40.066 --> 00:10:41.596
consider to be full virtual

00:10:41.596 --> 00:10:42.946
reality experiences.

00:10:43.686 --> 00:10:45.146
And, what I mean by that, is

00:10:45.146 --> 00:10:46.476
that the experiences take you to

00:10:46.476 --> 00:10:47.466
a different place.

00:10:47.836 --> 00:10:49.106
They really make you feel like

00:10:49.106 --> 00:10:50.166
you're somewhere else.

00:10:50.736 --> 00:10:51.846
You can walk around the

00:10:51.846 --> 00:10:52.556
environment.

00:10:52.886 --> 00:10:54.016
You can move around within it.

00:10:54.016 --> 00:10:55.616
You can look in all directions.

00:10:56.206 --> 00:10:57.566
And, to me that makes something

00:10:58.066 --> 00:10:59.706
really into a virtual reality

00:10:59.706 --> 00:11:01.266
experience, even if it is

00:11:01.266 --> 00:11:02.046
through a device.

00:11:02.456 --> 00:11:04.676
And, there's some benefits to

00:11:04.676 --> 00:11:04.946
that.

00:11:05.406 --> 00:11:06.466
You don't need any extra

00:11:06.466 --> 00:11:06.896
equipment.

00:11:06.896 --> 00:11:07.786
It works everywhere.

00:11:08.166 --> 00:11:09.246
You don't need to wear a headset

00:11:09.246 --> 00:11:09.936
on your head.

00:11:10.256 --> 00:11:11.706
It works everywhere you are with

00:11:11.706 --> 00:11:12.856
the device you already have.

00:11:13.196 --> 00:11:13.946
You don't need any kind of

00:11:13.986 --> 00:11:15.446
trackers or anything else.

00:11:16.176 --> 00:11:17.826
And, there's some benefits to

00:11:18.226 --> 00:11:19.626
looking through a device rather

00:11:19.626 --> 00:11:21.336
than being fully immersed.

00:11:21.656 --> 00:11:22.336
Like, you're never going to

00:11:22.336 --> 00:11:23.796
accidentally walk into a wall

00:11:23.796 --> 00:11:25.116
because you always have your

00:11:25.116 --> 00:11:25.986
peripheral vision.

00:11:26.826 --> 00:11:28.496
So, ARKit can be a great way to

00:11:28.726 --> 00:11:30.066
make virtual reality

00:11:30.066 --> 00:11:30.826
experiences.

00:11:31.116 --> 00:11:32.026
We'll take a look at one.

00:11:32.886 --> 00:11:35.236
So, this is the virtual reality

00:11:35.236 --> 00:11:36.706
experience called "Enter the

00:11:36.706 --> 00:11:37.116
Room."

00:11:37.116 --> 00:11:38.256
And, it was developed by the

00:11:38.256 --> 00:11:39.636
International Committee of the

00:11:39.636 --> 00:11:40.296
Red Cross.

00:11:40.696 --> 00:11:44.056
And, in this experience, once

00:11:44.056 --> 00:11:45.146
you walk into the room, you can

00:11:45.146 --> 00:11:47.436
look around in all directions.

00:11:47.436 --> 00:11:49.326
You can move closer to things.

00:11:49.326 --> 00:11:50.316
You can inspect them.

00:11:50.596 --> 00:11:51.496
You can move farther away.

00:11:51.496 --> 00:11:54.086
And, the sound comes in, and it

00:11:54.086 --> 00:11:55.536
feels like it's coming in from

00:11:55.536 --> 00:11:56.796
outside the room, from all

00:11:56.796 --> 00:11:57.306
around you.

00:11:57.306 --> 00:11:59.446
And, that makes it into a really

00:11:59.446 --> 00:12:00.716
powerful experience.

00:12:00.716 --> 00:12:03.496
And, that's what you can do with

00:12:03.496 --> 00:12:05.326
virtual reality using ARKit.

00:12:05.836 --> 00:12:08.356
So, those are some of the more

00:12:08.356 --> 00:12:10.186
radical options of things that

00:12:10.186 --> 00:12:11.396
you can build with ARKit.

00:12:12.076 --> 00:12:13.986
We can also look at some tips

00:12:13.986 --> 00:12:15.206
and tricks that make sense no

00:12:15.206 --> 00:12:17.266
matter what kind of app it is

00:12:17.266 --> 00:12:17.936
that you're building.

00:12:18.356 --> 00:12:19.686
Whether it's a game, or a

00:12:19.686 --> 00:12:21.736
productivity app, these can work

00:12:21.736 --> 00:12:22.346
for everything.

00:12:22.926 --> 00:12:25.286
So, the first thing I want to

00:12:25.286 --> 00:12:28.256
talk about here is showing text

00:12:28.256 --> 00:12:28.656
in AR.

00:12:29.296 --> 00:12:30.546
Because text is really

00:12:30.586 --> 00:12:32.056
important.

00:12:32.546 --> 00:12:34.816
All kinds of AR apps have

00:12:34.916 --> 00:12:36.776
different reasons to show text.

00:12:37.136 --> 00:12:38.316
If it's a game, maybe you want

00:12:38.316 --> 00:12:40.046
to show the title of a level, or

00:12:40.046 --> 00:12:41.066
some instructions.

00:12:41.586 --> 00:12:42.956
Or, maybe for other kinds of

00:12:42.956 --> 00:12:44.046
apps, you want to label

00:12:44.046 --> 00:12:45.896
something in the world, label a

00:12:45.896 --> 00:12:46.866
virtual object.

00:12:47.326 --> 00:12:48.696
Maybe show some annotations.

00:12:49.616 --> 00:12:51.136
But, the important part, no

00:12:51.136 --> 00:12:52.406
matter what reason it is that

00:12:52.406 --> 00:12:54.116
you're showing this text, is to

00:12:54.116 --> 00:12:55.546
keep that text readable.

00:12:55.876 --> 00:12:57.836
Make it really easy to read.

00:12:59.726 --> 00:13:01.706
So, the simplest way to show

00:13:01.706 --> 00:13:03.826
text in AR, is to put it out

00:13:03.826 --> 00:13:04.966
into the world, to put it in

00:13:04.966 --> 00:13:05.616
perspective.

00:13:06.556 --> 00:13:07.546
And, you know, that can look

00:13:07.546 --> 00:13:08.286
really cool.

00:13:08.926 --> 00:13:10.656
But, it also has some drawbacks.

00:13:11.386 --> 00:13:12.916
And, one of those drawbacks is

00:13:12.916 --> 00:13:14.096
what happens when you look at it

00:13:14.536 --> 00:13:15.286
from an angle.

00:13:15.886 --> 00:13:17.066
The letters can, sort of, squish

00:13:17.066 --> 00:13:17.656
together.

00:13:17.656 --> 00:13:18.896
It can be a little hard to read.

00:13:19.996 --> 00:13:21.576
And, another issue is what

00:13:21.576 --> 00:13:23.126
happens when you take a step

00:13:23.126 --> 00:13:24.096
back, when you're looking from

00:13:24.096 --> 00:13:24.866
further away.

00:13:25.386 --> 00:13:26.826
The text can get really small.

00:13:26.826 --> 00:13:27.726
It's like trying to read a piece

00:13:27.726 --> 00:13:29.616
of paper from all the way across

00:13:29.646 --> 00:13:30.116
the room.

00:13:30.746 --> 00:13:32.636
So, if you're showing titles, or

00:13:32.906 --> 00:13:34.126
other kinds of things that maybe

00:13:34.126 --> 00:13:35.246
people already know, or could

00:13:35.246 --> 00:13:36.886
get in another way, it can be

00:13:36.886 --> 00:13:37.946
really cool to show that in

00:13:37.946 --> 00:13:38.596
perspective.

00:13:38.756 --> 00:13:40.306
But, if you're showing something

00:13:40.306 --> 00:13:41.636
that people really need to read,

00:13:41.636 --> 00:13:43.736
need to get information from,

00:13:44.266 --> 00:13:44.966
you might want to try a

00:13:44.966 --> 00:13:45.706
different option.

00:13:45.846 --> 00:13:48.986
So, a different option that you

00:13:48.986 --> 00:13:51.036
can use, is to show your text in

00:13:51.036 --> 00:13:51.866
screen space.

00:13:52.706 --> 00:13:53.966
And, what I mean by screen

00:13:53.966 --> 00:13:55.496
space, is that the text is

00:13:55.586 --> 00:13:57.116
always the same size.

00:13:57.576 --> 00:13:58.956
It's always facing you.

00:13:58.956 --> 00:14:00.086
It's always head-on.

00:14:00.686 --> 00:14:01.896
And, that makes it really easy

00:14:01.896 --> 00:14:02.186
to read.

00:14:02.186 --> 00:14:03.596
It doesn't have those problems

00:14:03.906 --> 00:14:05.236
of what angle you're looking at,

00:14:05.576 --> 00:14:06.946
or how far away from it you are.

00:14:08.286 --> 00:14:09.546
But, the important part of

00:14:09.546 --> 00:14:11.806
showing text in screen space, is

00:14:11.806 --> 00:14:13.626
that it's still attached to a

00:14:13.626 --> 00:14:14.706
position in the world.

00:14:15.126 --> 00:14:16.976
It's still fixed to the place in

00:14:16.976 --> 00:14:18.166
the world that you attach it to

00:14:18.166 --> 00:14:20.476
an object, or attach it to some

00:14:20.476 --> 00:14:21.366
physical feature.

00:14:22.036 --> 00:14:24.166
And, that makes it really feel

00:14:24.166 --> 00:14:25.866
like part of the AR scene.

00:14:26.676 --> 00:14:28.796
So, screen space text is a great

00:14:28.796 --> 00:14:30.096
way to label things, put some

00:14:30.096 --> 00:14:32.646
annotations into AR, but still

00:14:32.646 --> 00:14:33.946
make them really readable.

00:14:34.516 --> 00:14:37.166
So, here's an example of screen

00:14:37.166 --> 00:14:37.626
space text.

00:14:37.626 --> 00:14:39.906
And, this is from Measure, which

00:14:39.906 --> 00:14:41.126
is part of iOS 12.

00:14:42.106 --> 00:14:43.046
When Measure shows the

00:14:43.046 --> 00:14:44.616
measurements, it shows them in

00:14:44.616 --> 00:14:45.626
screen space.

00:14:45.796 --> 00:14:47.046
So, no matter what angle you're

00:14:47.046 --> 00:14:48.016
looking at those measurements

00:14:48.016 --> 00:14:49.866
from, or how far away you are,

00:14:50.546 --> 00:14:51.756
they're always incredibly

00:14:51.756 --> 00:14:51.976
readable.

00:14:56.576 --> 00:14:59.126
So, screen space text is great

00:14:59.126 --> 00:14:59.956
for readability.

00:15:00.726 --> 00:15:01.766
But, you should still try and

00:15:01.836 --> 00:15:03.376
keep how much text it is that

00:15:03.586 --> 00:15:04.946
you're actually showing in AR to

00:15:04.946 --> 00:15:06.606
as little as possible.

00:15:07.146 --> 00:15:08.756
And, the reasons for that is

00:15:08.756 --> 00:15:10.126
when text is placed in the

00:15:10.126 --> 00:15:12.226
world, you always have to keep

00:15:12.226 --> 00:15:13.866
pointing your device at it in

00:15:13.866 --> 00:15:14.546
order to read it.

00:15:15.156 --> 00:15:16.346
If you turn your device to a

00:15:16.346 --> 00:15:17.776
more natural reading position,

00:15:18.266 --> 00:15:19.536
the text is going to go away.

00:15:20.786 --> 00:15:22.916
So, if you have more detailed

00:15:22.916 --> 00:15:24.376
text, if you're showing details

00:15:24.806 --> 00:15:26.126
about some kind of object, or

00:15:26.126 --> 00:15:27.756
something in the world, you

00:15:27.756 --> 00:15:29.446
should show those details on the

00:15:29.446 --> 00:15:30.126
display.

00:15:30.206 --> 00:15:31.746
And then, people can use all

00:15:31.746 --> 00:15:33.456
that experience that they built

00:15:33.456 --> 00:15:35.996
up using iOS and reading things

00:15:35.996 --> 00:15:38.636
on their devices, to read those

00:15:38.666 --> 00:15:40.546
details directly on the display.

00:15:41.926 --> 00:15:43.166
And, when you're showing those

00:15:43.166 --> 00:15:44.276
details, when you're coming out

00:15:44.276 --> 00:15:46.146
of AR, it's important to have a

00:15:46.146 --> 00:15:46.896
transition.

00:15:47.596 --> 00:15:48.916
Because those transitions can

00:15:48.916 --> 00:15:51.016
make it really clear what it is

00:15:51.016 --> 00:15:51.706
you're looking at.

00:15:52.246 --> 00:15:55.066
What text, what object it is

00:15:55.246 --> 00:15:56.786
that those details are

00:15:56.786 --> 00:15:57.456
referencing.

00:15:57.786 --> 00:15:58.886
What it is that you're getting

00:15:58.886 --> 00:15:59.706
details about.

00:15:59.706 --> 00:16:02.526
So, let's look at an example

00:16:02.526 --> 00:16:02.866
there.

00:16:02.986 --> 00:16:04.476
And, this is also from Measure.

00:16:05.606 --> 00:16:07.666
In Measure, when you tap on a

00:16:07.666 --> 00:16:09.796
measurement, it comes out of AR

00:16:09.866 --> 00:16:11.076
to show the details about that

00:16:11.076 --> 00:16:13.256
measurement flat on the screen.

00:16:13.256 --> 00:16:15.396
And that's great because it's

00:16:15.396 --> 00:16:16.076
really easy to read.

00:16:16.076 --> 00:16:17.626
You don't have to point your

00:16:17.846 --> 00:16:19.126
device or your phone at the

00:16:19.126 --> 00:16:20.616
measurement in order to read it.

00:16:21.026 --> 00:16:22.396
But, it's also really clear,

00:16:22.606 --> 00:16:23.826
because of the transitions.

00:16:24.446 --> 00:16:27.746
The transitions show you what

00:16:28.236 --> 00:16:29.966
measurement it is that you're

00:16:29.966 --> 00:16:31.246
looking at details for.

00:16:31.706 --> 00:16:32.786
And, they comes out of the

00:16:32.786 --> 00:16:34.136
measurement, so you're never

00:16:34.136 --> 00:16:35.186
going to be confused.

00:16:37.046 --> 00:16:38.366
So, transitions.

00:16:38.466 --> 00:16:40.036
They're really great when you're

00:16:40.036 --> 00:16:42.006
coming out of AR, and going back

00:16:42.006 --> 00:16:44.086
into AR, for showing details on

00:16:44.086 --> 00:16:44.756
the display.

00:16:45.706 --> 00:16:46.616
But, they're also really

00:16:46.616 --> 00:16:47.916
important when you're just

00:16:47.916 --> 00:16:49.206
showing objects in AR.

00:16:50.086 --> 00:16:51.236
And, that's because it makes it

00:16:51.236 --> 00:16:53.356
feel like there's one version of

00:16:53.356 --> 00:16:53.996
the object.

00:16:54.516 --> 00:16:55.946
It makes it feel like that

00:16:55.946 --> 00:16:57.706
object has its own identity.

00:16:57.826 --> 00:17:00.186
And, that's important, because

00:17:00.186 --> 00:17:01.996
things in AR are so physical.

00:17:02.346 --> 00:17:04.165
They have that physical sense.

00:17:04.506 --> 00:17:05.925
When you see them in AR, they

00:17:05.925 --> 00:17:06.516
look real.

00:17:07.306 --> 00:17:08.546
And, things in reality, you

00:17:08.546 --> 00:17:09.455
can't just copy them.

00:17:09.455 --> 00:17:10.516
You can't just make multiple

00:17:10.516 --> 00:17:11.036
copies.

00:17:11.796 --> 00:17:13.086
So, it's important to keep that

00:17:13.086 --> 00:17:14.606
same principle when you're

00:17:14.606 --> 00:17:16.056
showing objects in AR.

00:17:16.656 --> 00:17:18.816
So, this is what happens when

00:17:18.816 --> 00:17:20.366
you Quicklook at objects in AR.

00:17:21.276 --> 00:17:22.856
And, it shows a great example of

00:17:22.925 --> 00:17:23.915
keeping that identity.

00:17:24.496 --> 00:17:25.566
When you switch from the object

00:17:25.566 --> 00:17:28.096
tab to the AR tab, the object

00:17:28.146 --> 00:17:29.006
stays in place.

00:17:29.006 --> 00:17:30.366
It always stays visible.

00:17:30.366 --> 00:17:31.856
It doesn't disappear and then

00:17:31.856 --> 00:17:32.846
come from somewhere else.

00:17:33.676 --> 00:17:35.086
And, even when you're deciding

00:17:35.086 --> 00:17:36.586
where to place the object here,

00:17:37.546 --> 00:17:39.576
it always stays visible on the

00:17:39.576 --> 00:17:40.186
display.

00:17:40.616 --> 00:17:42.446
So, it's really easy to see that

00:17:42.446 --> 00:17:43.546
there's one version of this

00:17:43.546 --> 00:17:43.996
object.

00:17:44.916 --> 00:17:46.446
And, even when you go back into

00:17:46.446 --> 00:17:47.726
the app that you were

00:17:47.726 --> 00:17:50.166
Quicklooking the object from, it

00:17:50.166 --> 00:17:51.906
still shows the object

00:17:51.906 --> 00:17:53.076
transitioning back to where it

00:17:53.076 --> 00:17:53.666
came from.

00:17:54.206 --> 00:17:55.136
So, it feels like there's one

00:17:55.136 --> 00:17:57.156
object moving between different

00:17:57.156 --> 00:17:58.156
parts of your app.

00:17:58.486 --> 00:17:59.636
And then, into the world, and

00:17:59.636 --> 00:18:00.516
back out of the world.

00:18:00.866 --> 00:18:01.906
It doesn't feel like there's

00:18:01.906 --> 00:18:02.726
multiple copies.

00:18:03.126 --> 00:18:06.506
Alright. So, that was a bunch of

00:18:06.506 --> 00:18:09.086
information in a row about the

00:18:09.086 --> 00:18:10.006
different ways that you can

00:18:10.006 --> 00:18:11.476
present your content in AR.

00:18:12.546 --> 00:18:13.766
So, let's do a quick recap of

00:18:13.766 --> 00:18:14.066
that.

00:18:15.046 --> 00:18:16.586
So, first, we looked at the

00:18:16.586 --> 00:18:17.996
different ways you can make AR

00:18:17.996 --> 00:18:19.806
experiences, and we talked about

00:18:20.096 --> 00:18:21.986
using AR to create entirely 2D

00:18:21.986 --> 00:18:23.766
experiences, with no camera

00:18:23.766 --> 00:18:25.296
preview, and no 3D graphics.

00:18:26.536 --> 00:18:28.546
We talked about how VR can be a

00:18:28.546 --> 00:18:30.136
great way to build experiences

00:18:30.136 --> 00:18:31.876
with ARKit, and make you feel

00:18:31.876 --> 00:18:33.486
like you're somewhere else, that

00:18:33.816 --> 00:18:35.196
can be really powerful and

00:18:35.196 --> 00:18:35.926
really immersive.

00:18:37.186 --> 00:18:38.446
We talked about using screen

00:18:38.446 --> 00:18:41.406
space to show text in AR, to

00:18:41.406 --> 00:18:43.586
make it really readable from any

00:18:43.586 --> 00:18:45.416
angle, and readable from any

00:18:45.416 --> 00:18:45.876
distance.

00:18:47.186 --> 00:18:48.226
We talked about showing your

00:18:48.226 --> 00:18:50.576
details on the screen, so that

00:18:50.576 --> 00:18:51.516
they're easy to read without

00:18:51.596 --> 00:18:53.406
pointing your device at some

00:18:53.406 --> 00:18:55.036
specific place in the world.

00:18:55.116 --> 00:18:57.396
And that you can use all of that

00:18:57.396 --> 00:18:58.546
same knowledge that you've built

00:18:58.546 --> 00:19:00.336
up reading things on iOS.

00:19:01.046 --> 00:19:03.566
And finally, we talked about

00:19:03.566 --> 00:19:05.766
transitioning into AR, and out

00:19:05.766 --> 00:19:08.436
of AR, for showing details flat

00:19:08.436 --> 00:19:09.266
on the display.

00:19:09.666 --> 00:19:11.066
But, also to give objects that

00:19:11.066 --> 00:19:12.676
sense of identity, that sense of

00:19:12.676 --> 00:19:14.826
physicality that's so important

00:19:14.826 --> 00:19:14.976
in AR.

00:19:19.516 --> 00:19:21.246
Alright. So, that's presenting

00:19:21.246 --> 00:19:22.026
content in AR.

00:19:22.026 --> 00:19:23.196
So, different ways that you can

00:19:23.196 --> 00:19:23.916
present it.

00:19:23.916 --> 00:19:25.726
And some tips for different

00:19:26.136 --> 00:19:27.246
types of content that you're

00:19:27.246 --> 00:19:28.586
going to want to show in your AR

00:19:28.586 --> 00:19:28.936
apps.

00:19:30.226 --> 00:19:31.906
Now, let's talk about how we can

00:19:31.906 --> 00:19:33.636
interact with that content.

00:19:33.636 --> 00:19:35.006
Let's talk about interactions

00:19:35.366 --> 00:19:36.736
that make sense in the world.

00:19:37.236 --> 00:19:39.666
And, let's start with touch,

00:19:40.466 --> 00:19:41.786
because touch has been really

00:19:41.786 --> 00:19:43.646
important all the way back to

00:19:43.646 --> 00:19:44.876
the beginning of iOS.

00:19:45.196 --> 00:19:46.636
Multi-touch was there right from

00:19:46.636 --> 00:19:48.286
the start, and it's been the

00:19:48.286 --> 00:19:49.836
most important way to interact

00:19:49.836 --> 00:19:50.586
with our devices.

00:19:51.706 --> 00:19:53.026
And the reason touch is so

00:19:53.026 --> 00:19:54.386
important, the reason touch is

00:19:54.386 --> 00:19:56.506
so great, is that it enables

00:19:56.506 --> 00:19:57.606
direct manipulation.

00:19:58.106 --> 00:20:00.586
And, direct manipulation is when

00:20:00.586 --> 00:20:02.116
you interact directly with

00:20:02.116 --> 00:20:03.606
things on the screen, like

00:20:03.606 --> 00:20:04.956
they're physical objects.

00:20:05.446 --> 00:20:07.396
You're not using controls to

00:20:07.646 --> 00:20:09.386
scroll or to pinch to zoom.

00:20:09.696 --> 00:20:11.036
You're interacting directly with

00:20:11.036 --> 00:20:11.696
the content.

00:20:12.136 --> 00:20:13.126
It's like there's a physical

00:20:13.126 --> 00:20:14.826
thing that you're manipulating.

00:20:15.346 --> 00:20:17.646
And, that's even more important

00:20:17.646 --> 00:20:18.286
in AR.

00:20:18.696 --> 00:20:20.486
Because in AR, as I said before,

00:20:20.786 --> 00:20:21.876
things are really physical.

00:20:21.876 --> 00:20:23.306
Objects feel like they're real.

00:20:24.246 --> 00:20:25.506
They feel like part of the real

00:20:25.506 --> 00:20:25.966
world.

00:20:26.516 --> 00:20:28.286
So, it's really important to use

00:20:28.286 --> 00:20:29.866
direct manipulation to make it

00:20:29.866 --> 00:20:30.926
feel like you're interacting

00:20:30.926 --> 00:20:32.726
directly with those objects.

00:20:34.336 --> 00:20:36.226
And, direct manipulation is also

00:20:36.226 --> 00:20:38.496
great because it uses gestures

00:20:38.556 --> 00:20:40.166
that you already know, that you

00:20:40.166 --> 00:20:41.716
have experience with from iOS.

00:20:42.746 --> 00:20:44.226
Because those gestures will be

00:20:44.226 --> 00:20:46.116
the same as any other content on

00:20:46.116 --> 00:20:46.326
iOS.

00:20:47.126 --> 00:20:48.456
They're things that you've been

00:20:48.456 --> 00:20:50.396
using for probably a long time.

00:20:50.876 --> 00:20:53.836
So, the first one there is how

00:20:53.836 --> 00:20:56.036
you can move objects in AR with

00:20:56.036 --> 00:20:57.056
direct manipulation.

00:20:57.566 --> 00:20:59.246
If you want to move objects, you

00:20:59.246 --> 00:21:00.256
just put your finger down and

00:21:00.256 --> 00:21:01.516
drag them to a new place.

00:21:02.086 --> 00:21:02.756
And, it feels like you're

00:21:02.756 --> 00:21:04.526
picking up the object, because

00:21:04.526 --> 00:21:05.716
it stays under your finger.

00:21:05.716 --> 00:21:07.346
You get this physical connection

00:21:07.346 --> 00:21:08.796
to the thing that you're moving.

00:21:11.216 --> 00:21:13.606
Another gesture you can do, is

00:21:13.606 --> 00:21:14.796
scaling objects.

00:21:15.346 --> 00:21:17.226
So, in AR, things start out at

00:21:17.226 --> 00:21:18.466
their physical size, at their

00:21:18.466 --> 00:21:19.506
natural size.

00:21:19.986 --> 00:21:21.146
But, if you want to change that,

00:21:21.436 --> 00:21:22.736
you can pinch the object to make

00:21:22.736 --> 00:21:23.216
it bigger.

00:21:23.766 --> 00:21:24.766
And, you can pinch out on the

00:21:24.766 --> 00:21:25.836
object if you want to make it

00:21:25.836 --> 00:21:26.376
smaller.

00:21:27.286 --> 00:21:28.246
The important things to think

00:21:28.246 --> 00:21:29.206
about when you're scaling

00:21:29.206 --> 00:21:31.176
objects in AR, is to give some

00:21:31.176 --> 00:21:32.436
feedback when you're doing it.

00:21:32.836 --> 00:21:34.016
Because the change is really,

00:21:34.016 --> 00:21:35.406
really big when you take an

00:21:35.406 --> 00:21:36.796
object and scale it up to 4

00:21:36.796 --> 00:21:37.666
times the size.

00:21:38.496 --> 00:21:40.036
So, it's important to give

00:21:40.036 --> 00:21:41.466
people feedback, so they

00:21:41.466 --> 00:21:42.726
absolutely know what happened.

00:21:43.626 --> 00:21:44.996
And, the second thing is to make

00:21:44.996 --> 00:21:47.056
it really easy to go -- to take

00:21:47.056 --> 00:21:48.636
the object back to its natural

00:21:48.636 --> 00:21:49.146
size.

00:21:49.526 --> 00:21:50.536
Back to the size that it would

00:21:50.536 --> 00:21:51.846
be in the physical world.

00:21:52.236 --> 00:21:54.496
So, you can snap back to 100%,

00:21:54.886 --> 00:21:56.186
maybe with a haptic, to make

00:21:56.186 --> 00:21:56.966
that really easy.

00:21:57.416 --> 00:22:01.316
Another thing you can do is

00:22:01.396 --> 00:22:03.366
rotate objects, by putting two

00:22:03.366 --> 00:22:04.946
fingers on the display, and

00:22:04.946 --> 00:22:06.036
twisting to rotate.

00:22:07.036 --> 00:22:08.296
And, that can be really great,

00:22:08.296 --> 00:22:09.606
but with all of these two finger

00:22:09.606 --> 00:22:11.286
gestures, another thing you

00:22:11.286 --> 00:22:12.986
should think about is your tap

00:22:12.986 --> 00:22:13.546
targets.

00:22:14.186 --> 00:22:15.866
Because things in AR are always

00:22:15.866 --> 00:22:16.786
moving as you're moving the

00:22:16.786 --> 00:22:18.586
device, and they can get really

00:22:18.586 --> 00:22:20.086
small if you get further away,

00:22:20.086 --> 00:22:21.206
or if you scale them down.

00:22:21.756 --> 00:22:22.546
You should make sure to use

00:22:22.706 --> 00:22:24.406
really generous tap targets.

00:22:24.826 --> 00:22:26.096
So, it's easy to land two

00:22:26.096 --> 00:22:27.396
fingers on the object.

00:22:28.076 --> 00:22:29.556
And, be sure to use the center

00:22:29.556 --> 00:22:31.656
of those two finger touch

00:22:31.656 --> 00:22:33.406
positions to figure out which

00:22:33.406 --> 00:22:34.526
object to interact with.

00:22:34.876 --> 00:22:35.826
Because you might not be able to

00:22:35.826 --> 00:22:38.156
land two whole fingers, even on

00:22:38.156 --> 00:22:39.766
a generous tap target in AR.

00:22:40.266 --> 00:22:43.676
Alright, so direct manipulation

00:22:43.676 --> 00:22:45.126
is really great in AR.

00:22:45.126 --> 00:22:46.806
It's really important because AR

00:22:46.806 --> 00:22:47.536
is so physical.

00:22:48.436 --> 00:22:50.686
But, it's also not quite enough

00:22:50.686 --> 00:22:51.696
for most AR apps.

00:22:51.696 --> 00:22:53.346
Because if you have a lot of

00:22:53.346 --> 00:22:54.406
objects, it can make it hard to

00:22:54.406 --> 00:22:55.376
touch the right one.

00:22:55.716 --> 00:22:56.936
As I said before, the objects

00:22:56.936 --> 00:22:59.366
are always moving on the display

00:22:59.366 --> 00:23:00.296
as you're looking at different

00:23:00.296 --> 00:23:01.166
places in the world.

00:23:01.486 --> 00:23:02.456
And, they're staying fixed to

00:23:02.456 --> 00:23:03.446
that place in the world.

00:23:03.446 --> 00:23:05.256
So, it can be a little hard to

00:23:05.316 --> 00:23:07.096
aim for those objects on the

00:23:07.096 --> 00:23:07.666
screen.

00:23:08.426 --> 00:23:10.786
But, the fundamental reason, the

00:23:10.786 --> 00:23:12.226
number one reason, the real

00:23:12.226 --> 00:23:15.206
reason that touch is not enough

00:23:15.456 --> 00:23:17.266
for AR apps, is that it's

00:23:17.266 --> 00:23:18.826
fundamentally two-dimensional.

00:23:19.536 --> 00:23:20.846
The surface of the display is

00:23:20.846 --> 00:23:22.006
two-dimensional, and you're

00:23:22.006 --> 00:23:23.236
touching on that surface.

00:23:23.236 --> 00:23:25.126
That is what made it so great,

00:23:25.126 --> 00:23:27.566
multi-touch so great for flat,

00:23:27.566 --> 00:23:28.936
2D apps in iOS.

00:23:29.596 --> 00:23:31.376
But, AR content, it's placed

00:23:31.376 --> 00:23:32.026
into the world.

00:23:32.026 --> 00:23:33.226
It's part of the world.

00:23:33.716 --> 00:23:35.856
So, that means we need some way

00:23:35.856 --> 00:23:37.266
to interact with that content

00:23:37.636 --> 00:23:38.846
also in three dimensions.

00:23:38.966 --> 00:23:40.196
Because the world is

00:23:40.196 --> 00:23:40.866
three-dimensional.

00:23:42.576 --> 00:23:44.566
The answer there is moving your

00:23:44.566 --> 00:23:45.186
device.

00:23:45.646 --> 00:23:47.026
Because moving your device, it's

00:23:47.026 --> 00:23:48.436
natively three-dimensional.

00:23:48.796 --> 00:23:49.686
It's three-dimensional

00:23:49.686 --> 00:23:50.286
inherently.

00:23:50.626 --> 00:23:51.966
You can move up and down.

00:23:52.176 --> 00:23:53.126
You can move left and right.

00:23:53.126 --> 00:23:54.826
You can move forward and back.

00:23:55.136 --> 00:23:56.506
You can turn in all directions.

00:23:56.506 --> 00:23:58.446
You can stand up and move across

00:23:58.486 --> 00:23:59.826
the room if you want to go a

00:23:59.826 --> 00:24:00.666
little bit further.

00:24:01.506 --> 00:24:03.746
But, the important part is that

00:24:03.746 --> 00:24:05.446
moving your device is fully

00:24:05.446 --> 00:24:06.236
three-dimensional, and that

00:24:06.236 --> 00:24:07.676
really makes it the number one,

00:24:07.676 --> 00:24:09.756
the primary interaction in AR.

00:24:10.716 --> 00:24:12.506
In fact, I would say that moving

00:24:12.506 --> 00:24:14.166
your device is more important

00:24:14.166 --> 00:24:17.096
than touch for AR apps.

00:24:17.146 --> 00:24:18.766
In fact, it's so natural, it's

00:24:18.766 --> 00:24:21.356
built in to every AR app by

00:24:21.356 --> 00:24:21.886
default.

00:24:22.376 --> 00:24:23.156
The way that you look at

00:24:23.156 --> 00:24:24.726
different things in AR is by

00:24:24.726 --> 00:24:26.676
moving your device to look at it

00:24:26.676 --> 00:24:27.886
from different angles, and

00:24:27.886 --> 00:24:28.726
different positions.

00:24:29.326 --> 00:24:31.206
So, it's really natural, and

00:24:31.206 --> 00:24:32.506
it's also really powerful.

00:24:34.176 --> 00:24:35.506
And, moving your device, it

00:24:35.506 --> 00:24:37.066
accomplishes many of the things

00:24:37.436 --> 00:24:38.766
that you would have done in a 2D

00:24:38.766 --> 00:24:40.746
app by using multi-touch.

00:24:41.136 --> 00:24:42.846
So, in a 2D app, if you want to

00:24:42.846 --> 00:24:44.756
see more content, the way you do

00:24:44.756 --> 00:24:45.996
that is by scrolling on the

00:24:45.996 --> 00:24:46.646
display.

00:24:46.966 --> 00:24:48.446
You scroll down to see something

00:24:48.446 --> 00:24:48.726
new.

00:24:49.696 --> 00:24:51.206
And, that's great in a 2D app,

00:24:51.956 --> 00:24:54.656
but in AR, you do that in 3D.

00:24:54.796 --> 00:24:56.456
You see different content, by

00:24:56.456 --> 00:24:59.006
moving your device to look at

00:24:59.246 --> 00:25:00.326
the content from different

00:25:00.326 --> 00:25:01.806
positions, and from different

00:25:01.806 --> 00:25:02.266
angles.

00:25:02.836 --> 00:25:04.586
So, it solves that same problem

00:25:04.586 --> 00:25:06.196
of wanting to see more, but it

00:25:06.196 --> 00:25:07.376
solves it fully in three

00:25:07.376 --> 00:25:07.996
dimensions.

00:25:09.396 --> 00:25:11.096
Similarly, in a traditional 2D

00:25:11.096 --> 00:25:11.956
app, if you want to see

00:25:11.956 --> 00:25:13.786
something bigger, you pinch in

00:25:13.786 --> 00:25:14.696
on it to make it bigger.

00:25:14.696 --> 00:25:15.676
You pinch to zoom.

00:25:16.026 --> 00:25:17.806
If you want to see it smaller,

00:25:18.136 --> 00:25:19.216
you pinch out.

00:25:19.476 --> 00:25:21.126
You pinch to zoom out.

00:25:22.386 --> 00:25:24.096
But, in AR, if you want to see

00:25:24.096 --> 00:25:25.546
something bigger, you can just

00:25:25.546 --> 00:25:26.666
get closer to the thing you're

00:25:26.666 --> 00:25:27.106
looking at.

00:25:27.106 --> 00:25:28.346
You can just move closer in.

00:25:28.346 --> 00:25:30.116
And, if you want to see more

00:25:30.116 --> 00:25:31.716
things at once, you want to see

00:25:31.716 --> 00:25:34.046
things from a wider angle, you

00:25:34.046 --> 00:25:35.976
can just take a step back, and

00:25:35.976 --> 00:25:37.156
look at all of the content at

00:25:37.156 --> 00:25:37.516
once.

00:25:38.646 --> 00:25:41.426
So, moving your device, it also

00:25:41.426 --> 00:25:42.906
replaces what you might have

00:25:42.906 --> 00:25:44.546
done by pinch to zoom to see

00:25:44.546 --> 00:25:47.816
more content in a 2D

00:25:47.816 --> 00:25:48.536
application.

00:25:50.326 --> 00:25:52.116
So, movement is really great.

00:25:52.116 --> 00:25:53.756
It can replace some of those

00:25:53.756 --> 00:25:54.596
things you might have used

00:25:54.596 --> 00:25:55.506
multi-touch for.

00:25:56.056 --> 00:25:57.846
You can also use it to build

00:25:57.846 --> 00:26:00.396
totally custom interactions for

00:26:00.396 --> 00:26:01.026
your AR apps.

00:26:01.856 --> 00:26:02.786
And, those can be really

00:26:02.786 --> 00:26:03.326
natural.

00:26:03.646 --> 00:26:05.456
Just like using your device to

00:26:05.456 --> 00:26:06.736
look around at different things,

00:26:06.736 --> 00:26:07.766
or to get closer and further

00:26:07.766 --> 00:26:08.186
away.

00:26:08.766 --> 00:26:09.856
So, let's take a look at an

00:26:09.856 --> 00:26:10.726
example of that.

00:26:11.426 --> 00:26:12.886
This is Swiftshot, the

00:26:12.886 --> 00:26:14.576
multiplayer AR sample game that

00:26:14.856 --> 00:26:15.506
you might have seen in the

00:26:15.506 --> 00:26:16.306
Keynote, or you might have

00:26:16.306 --> 00:26:16.996
actually tried it.

00:26:17.806 --> 00:26:19.556
In order to fire a slingshot in

00:26:19.556 --> 00:26:21.246
Swiftshot, the way you do it is

00:26:21.246 --> 00:26:22.586
you move close to that

00:26:22.586 --> 00:26:23.136
slingshot.

00:26:23.546 --> 00:26:24.266
You don't have to pick which

00:26:24.266 --> 00:26:25.296
slingshot you're going to fire

00:26:25.296 --> 00:26:25.976
from a list.

00:26:26.346 --> 00:26:27.296
You don't have to reach out and

00:26:27.296 --> 00:26:28.256
try and aim for it on the

00:26:28.256 --> 00:26:28.726
screen.

00:26:29.036 --> 00:26:30.906
You just move close to it, and

00:26:30.906 --> 00:26:31.716
when you want to fire the

00:26:31.716 --> 00:26:33.516
slingshot, you just pull back

00:26:33.516 --> 00:26:34.016
and release.

00:26:35.056 --> 00:26:37.046
So, it's incredibly precise,

00:26:37.046 --> 00:26:38.516
because you can fire in three

00:26:38.836 --> 00:26:39.386
dimensions.

00:26:39.386 --> 00:26:40.366
You have three dimensions of

00:26:40.366 --> 00:26:41.976
precision while you're moving

00:26:41.976 --> 00:26:42.886
that slingshot, while you're

00:26:42.886 --> 00:26:43.546
pulling it back.

00:26:44.256 --> 00:26:45.406
And, that's more than you could

00:26:45.406 --> 00:26:47.156
ever do using touch.

00:26:47.686 --> 00:26:49.196
So, moving your device, it's not

00:26:49.196 --> 00:26:50.786
only really natural, but it's

00:26:50.786 --> 00:26:52.866
also more precise than you could

00:26:52.866 --> 00:26:57.836
ever do using touch in AR apps.

00:26:58.046 --> 00:26:59.756
So, moving your device is great,

00:27:00.076 --> 00:27:01.906
but sometimes we need to combine

00:27:02.016 --> 00:27:04.026
the best of touch and the best

00:27:04.026 --> 00:27:05.926
of device movement to create the

00:27:05.926 --> 00:27:07.336
absolute best interactions.

00:27:08.456 --> 00:27:09.956
So, let's look at some examples

00:27:09.956 --> 00:27:10.326
of that.

00:27:10.326 --> 00:27:12.226
And, let's start with combining

00:27:12.226 --> 00:27:14.626
direct manipulation with moving

00:27:15.306 --> 00:27:16.546
your device.

00:27:16.666 --> 00:27:19.086
So, Quicklook in AR also offers

00:27:19.086 --> 00:27:20.936
a great example of combining

00:27:20.936 --> 00:27:23.166
device movement and direct

00:27:23.266 --> 00:27:25.216
manipulation in AR.

00:27:26.126 --> 00:27:27.386
If you want to move an object,

00:27:27.386 --> 00:27:29.056
of course, you can just drag it

00:27:29.056 --> 00:27:30.736
to the new position, the same as

00:27:30.736 --> 00:27:31.596
you saw before.

00:27:31.916 --> 00:27:33.116
Touch on the screen and move it

00:27:33.116 --> 00:27:33.906
to a new place.

00:27:34.436 --> 00:27:35.886
But, you could also touch down

00:27:35.886 --> 00:27:37.706
to pick up the object and then

00:27:37.706 --> 00:27:39.586
turn the device and release in a

00:27:39.586 --> 00:27:40.156
new place.

00:27:40.286 --> 00:27:42.336
And, that's great, because it

00:27:42.336 --> 00:27:43.076
gives you the full

00:27:43.076 --> 00:27:44.736
three-dimensional control of

00:27:44.736 --> 00:27:46.016
