mesh, in order to have it react

00:45:14.956 --> 00:45:16.666
realistically to the simulated

00:45:16.666 --> 00:45:18.866
lights found in your AR scene.

00:45:19.456 --> 00:45:20.546
And, moving forward, all the

00:45:20.546 --> 00:45:21.206
materials that we'll be

00:45:21.206 --> 00:45:22.696
discussing will conform to this

00:45:22.696 --> 00:45:23.436
shading technique.

00:45:24.586 --> 00:45:25.296
If you want further details

00:45:25.296 --> 00:45:26.376
about this concept, there's a

00:45:26.376 --> 00:45:29.596
great WWDC 2016 talk that goes

00:45:29.596 --> 00:45:30.896
over details about

00:45:30.896 --> 00:45:32.036
physically-based rendering as it

00:45:32.036 --> 00:45:33.186
applies to SceneKit, called

00:45:33.416 --> 00:45:34.736
Advances in SceneKit Rendering.

00:45:34.736 --> 00:45:37.276
Now, with that said, let's start

00:45:37.356 --> 00:45:38.466
talking about our first material

00:45:38.466 --> 00:45:40.056
property, albedo, or what is

00:45:40.056 --> 00:45:41.296
sometimes lovingly referred to

00:45:41.296 --> 00:45:42.836
as the base or diffuse color

00:45:42.836 --> 00:45:43.316
property.

00:45:44.616 --> 00:45:45.516
So, let's jump back into

00:45:45.516 --> 00:45:46.076
CampfiAR.

00:45:47.016 --> 00:45:48.006
Previously our base measure's

00:45:48.006 --> 00:45:48.886
looking a little bit boring,

00:45:49.146 --> 00:45:50.066
with the gray material

00:45:50.066 --> 00:45:51.626
associated with it, but after

00:45:51.676 --> 00:45:52.956
you apply albedo, you start to

00:45:52.956 --> 00:45:54.356
see that it looks a lot better.

00:45:54.766 --> 00:45:55.756
But, the campfire is still

00:45:55.756 --> 00:45:56.996
missing a lot of those small,

00:45:57.076 --> 00:45:58.436
finite details that were

00:45:58.436 --> 00:45:59.456
originally found in that

00:45:59.456 --> 00:46:00.406
high-density mesh.

00:46:01.076 --> 00:46:02.096
As you move closer to the

00:46:02.096 --> 00:46:04.046
campfire, you'll notice that all

00:46:04.046 --> 00:46:05.016
the surfaces are relatively

00:46:05.016 --> 00:46:05.366
flat.

00:46:05.936 --> 00:46:06.846
And, this is something that

00:46:06.846 --> 00:46:07.906
we'll definitely correct later,

00:46:07.906 --> 00:46:09.146
but first let's dive into the

00:46:09.146 --> 00:46:10.186
albedo property a little bit

00:46:10.186 --> 00:46:10.446
more.

00:46:12.016 --> 00:46:13.966
Think of the albedo as basically

00:46:13.966 --> 00:46:15.266
being the base mesh of the

00:46:15.266 --> 00:46:16.326
various objects in your AR

00:46:16.326 --> 00:46:16.656
scene.

00:46:17.526 --> 00:46:18.496
This is the material property

00:46:18.496 --> 00:46:20.246
that you typically use to apply

00:46:20.476 --> 00:46:22.076
textures to the surface of your

00:46:22.076 --> 00:46:22.376
model.

00:46:23.376 --> 00:46:24.676
If you recall, your mesh

00:46:24.676 --> 00:46:25.846
contained different vertices,

00:46:25.846 --> 00:46:26.946
that held different pieces of

00:46:26.946 --> 00:46:27.586
information.

00:46:28.856 --> 00:46:29.916
The ones you see here are

00:46:29.916 --> 00:46:31.286
actually called UV coordinates,

00:46:31.336 --> 00:46:33.166
which help map out how pixels

00:46:33.166 --> 00:46:34.236
from various texture maps are

00:46:34.236 --> 00:46:35.576
actually applied to the model.

00:46:36.606 --> 00:46:37.996
And, after we've worked with

00:46:37.996 --> 00:46:39.746
these textures, we've applied

00:46:39.746 --> 00:46:41.356
the abel material to this

00:46:41.356 --> 00:46:42.576
property on the fish.

00:46:43.996 --> 00:46:45.286
So, now we've essentially

00:46:45.286 --> 00:46:46.886
applied a texture to our fish, I

00:46:46.886 --> 00:46:47.856
want to remind you about the

00:46:47.856 --> 00:46:49.656
fact that you never know where

00:46:49.656 --> 00:46:50.206
people are never going to

00:46:50.206 --> 00:46:51.126
experience your app.

00:46:51.776 --> 00:46:52.896
You want to be able to have your

00:46:52.986 --> 00:46:54.506
content fit in as many different

00:46:54.506 --> 00:46:55.626
scenarios as possible.

00:46:55.706 --> 00:46:57.606
So, you want to take care in

00:46:57.606 --> 00:46:59.206
selecting the right albedo value

00:46:59.726 --> 00:47:01.056
that are neither too bright or

00:47:01.056 --> 00:47:01.416
dark.

00:47:01.956 --> 00:47:03.776
As, you want this to work in a

00:47:03.816 --> 00:47:04.746
wide variety of different

00:47:04.746 --> 00:47:05.456
situations.

00:47:06.146 --> 00:47:07.856
So, our fish has got a skin, but

00:47:07.856 --> 00:47:08.886
we're still missing a lot of

00:47:08.886 --> 00:47:10.286
details from this, and the other

00:47:10.286 --> 00:47:11.746
objects found in the scene.

00:47:12.136 --> 00:47:13.626
So let's go back into how we can

00:47:13.626 --> 00:47:14.636
start bringing back a lot of

00:47:14.636 --> 00:47:16.866
those details through the use of

00:47:16.866 --> 00:47:18.236
the normal material property.

00:47:18.296 --> 00:47:20.656
So, as we jump back into

00:47:20.656 --> 00:47:22.466
CampfiAR, let's see how we can

00:47:22.466 --> 00:47:23.916
bring back some of those details

00:47:23.916 --> 00:47:25.436
that we moved from optimization.

00:47:26.166 --> 00:47:27.476
This can be done through the use

00:47:27.476 --> 00:47:28.676
of a special texture called a

00:47:28.676 --> 00:47:30.706
normal map, which you can see

00:47:30.706 --> 00:47:32.056
here as the blue tinted maps

00:47:32.056 --> 00:47:33.476
that are now applied to our AR

00:47:33.476 --> 00:47:33.786
scene.

00:47:34.576 --> 00:47:36.016
These maps allow you to add

00:47:36.046 --> 00:47:38.276
those fine surface details back

00:47:38.276 --> 00:47:39.526
into your models, without the

00:47:39.526 --> 00:47:40.876
need to add any additional

00:47:40.876 --> 00:47:41.336
geometry.

00:47:42.036 --> 00:47:43.276
Now, after applying the normal

00:47:43.276 --> 00:47:45.046
maps, you can see how the fish

00:47:45.046 --> 00:47:46.676
exhibits some scales, as well as

00:47:46.676 --> 00:47:48.306
making the branches show just a

00:47:48.306 --> 00:47:49.256
tiny bit more detail.

00:47:49.966 --> 00:47:51.276
Also if you take a look at the

00:47:51.276 --> 00:47:52.296
statistics panel, you'll notice

00:47:52.296 --> 00:47:53.456
that there was absolutely no

00:47:53.456 --> 00:47:55.256
change in the number of polygons

00:47:55.376 --> 00:47:56.176
related to this model.

00:47:56.336 --> 00:47:58.946
It's magical, isn't it?

00:47:59.206 --> 00:48:01.236
So, how do we make this normal

00:48:01.236 --> 00:48:01.446
map?

00:48:02.146 --> 00:48:03.196
Let's see a closer look at one

00:48:03.196 --> 00:48:05.156
of the branches, and see what we

00:48:05.156 --> 00:48:06.216
can do to make this work.

00:48:06.626 --> 00:48:07.936
In most modern 3D modeling

00:48:07.936 --> 00:48:09.346
applications, artists have the

00:48:09.346 --> 00:48:10.406
ability to generate these normal

00:48:10.406 --> 00:48:12.496
maps by projecting details from

00:48:12.496 --> 00:48:14.236
a high-density mesh over to a

00:48:14.236 --> 00:48:14.986
low-density one.

00:48:15.546 --> 00:48:16.556
So, here you can see what the

00:48:16.556 --> 00:48:17.936
normal map looks like on the

00:48:17.936 --> 00:48:19.176
branches after they've been

00:48:19.176 --> 00:48:20.636
generated from this high-density

00:48:20.636 --> 00:48:21.046
mesh.

00:48:21.756 --> 00:48:23.296
And, after applying the normal

00:48:23.296 --> 00:48:24.786
map, you start to notice all

00:48:24.786 --> 00:48:25.826
those nice details that were

00:48:25.826 --> 00:48:27.276
originally lost come back into

00:48:27.276 --> 00:48:27.756
this model.

00:48:27.756 --> 00:48:28.876
But we still are able to

00:48:28.876 --> 00:48:30.446
maintain that high performance,

00:48:30.496 --> 00:48:31.656
of the low-poly mesh.

00:48:31.656 --> 00:48:34.386
So, you may be wondering why the

00:48:34.416 --> 00:48:35.456
normal map looks kind of

00:48:35.456 --> 00:48:37.356
strange, well the colors of the

00:48:37.356 --> 00:48:38.836
normal map actually represent

00:48:38.996 --> 00:48:40.626
visual representations of the

00:48:40.626 --> 00:48:41.236
vector data.

00:48:41.236 --> 00:48:43.816
And, determine how the normals

00:48:43.816 --> 00:48:45.446
on the surface model will be

00:48:45.446 --> 00:48:47.866
offset in order to change the

00:48:47.866 --> 00:48:48.566
way that light is being

00:48:48.566 --> 00:48:50.526
reflected, and our key to making

00:48:50.526 --> 00:48:51.196
this effect work.

00:48:51.706 --> 00:48:53.766
That was a bit of a mouthful, so

00:48:53.766 --> 00:48:54.936
let's dive a little bit more

00:48:54.936 --> 00:48:57.006
into this property, because

00:48:57.276 --> 00:48:58.636
normals we feel are a really

00:48:58.636 --> 00:48:59.326
important topic.

00:48:59.946 --> 00:49:00.946
And, we want to spend a couple

00:49:00.946 --> 00:49:02.846
more minutes just going into how

00:49:02.846 --> 00:49:04.786
truly spectacular these can be.

00:49:06.156 --> 00:49:07.206
The art of manipulating normal

00:49:07.206 --> 00:49:08.626
vectors are one of the key tools

00:49:08.626 --> 00:49:10.396
that AR creators have in order

00:49:10.396 --> 00:49:12.906
to add a lot of the significant

00:49:12.906 --> 00:49:14.416
details back into their model.

00:49:15.076 --> 00:49:16.706
So, what the heck is a normal

00:49:16.706 --> 00:49:18.206
vector, and are there strange

00:49:18.206 --> 00:49:19.016
vectors as well?

00:49:19.696 --> 00:49:20.916
Well, no there's no strange

00:49:20.916 --> 00:49:21.926
vectors unless you forgot your

00:49:21.926 --> 00:49:24.046
high school trig, but normal

00:49:24.046 --> 00:49:25.566
vectors lie perpendicular to the

00:49:25.566 --> 00:49:26.906
surface of the mesh, and are

00:49:26.906 --> 00:49:28.146
associated with each mesh

00:49:28.146 --> 00:49:28.766
vertex.

00:49:29.436 --> 00:49:30.266
So, why do we need these

00:49:30.266 --> 00:49:30.746
normals?

00:49:31.246 --> 00:49:33.406
Well, in order to see our

00:49:33.406 --> 00:49:34.666
object, you need to place

00:49:34.716 --> 00:49:36.416
simulated lights into your 3D

00:49:36.416 --> 00:49:36.936
engine.

00:49:37.796 --> 00:49:39.446
Normal vectors allow 3D engines

00:49:39.446 --> 00:49:40.826
to calculate how these lights

00:49:40.826 --> 00:49:41.906
are actually reflected off the

00:49:41.906 --> 00:49:43.126
surface of these materials.

00:49:43.616 --> 00:49:45.026
Similar to how light behaves in

00:49:45.026 --> 00:49:46.156
the real world, and are

00:49:46.156 --> 00:49:47.376
essential to making sure that

00:49:47.376 --> 00:49:49.286
your AR scenes mimic reality.

00:49:49.846 --> 00:49:52.016
What's interesting is that by

00:49:52.256 --> 00:49:53.786
modifying these normals, you can

00:49:53.786 --> 00:49:54.906
trick the engine to thinking

00:49:54.906 --> 00:49:56.156
that your surface is actually

00:49:56.156 --> 00:49:57.756
more detailed than it really is,

00:49:58.136 --> 00:49:59.276
without need to add any

00:49:59.276 --> 00:49:59.946
additional geometry.

00:50:00.046 --> 00:50:01.896
If you take a look at this

00:50:01.896 --> 00:50:03.246
example, you can see a simple

00:50:03.246 --> 00:50:04.866
sphere, being rendered with flat

00:50:04.866 --> 00:50:05.236
shading.

00:50:06.036 --> 00:50:06.836
What this means, that the

00:50:06.836 --> 00:50:08.196
normals associated with each

00:50:08.196 --> 00:50:09.776
face of the mesh are pointing in

00:50:09.776 --> 00:50:11.556
the exact same direction, as

00:50:11.556 --> 00:50:12.686
seen by the 2D diagram.

00:50:13.586 --> 00:50:15.376
Now, when you -- when light

00:50:15.376 --> 00:50:16.676
reacts to this surface, you'll

00:50:16.676 --> 00:50:18.366
be actually able to notice all

00:50:18.366 --> 00:50:19.936
the different polygons

00:50:19.936 --> 00:50:21.246
comprising this mesh due to

00:50:21.246 --> 00:50:22.856
being evenly lit across each

00:50:22.856 --> 00:50:23.286
face.

00:50:23.776 --> 00:50:25.866
Here, though, we're using the

00:50:25.866 --> 00:50:27.496
exact same model, but leveraging

00:50:27.496 --> 00:50:28.866
a technique called smooth or

00:50:28.866 --> 00:50:29.716
phong shading.

00:50:30.346 --> 00:50:31.756
Notice that the normals are

00:50:31.756 --> 00:50:33.186
actually gradually changing as

00:50:33.186 --> 00:50:34.356
you move across the surface of

00:50:34.356 --> 00:50:34.996
the polygon.

00:50:35.786 --> 00:50:37.736
With the engine calculates the

00:50:37.766 --> 00:50:40.076
reflection off of this model,

00:50:40.076 --> 00:50:41.096
it'll give the impression of a

00:50:41.096 --> 00:50:43.016
smooth, curved surface due to

00:50:43.016 --> 00:50:44.636
the gradual interpolation of

00:50:44.636 --> 00:50:45.296
these normals.

00:50:46.726 --> 00:50:48.206
What's really awesome is that

00:50:48.206 --> 00:50:49.486
these two models have the exact

00:50:49.486 --> 00:50:50.366
same number of polygons

00:50:50.366 --> 00:50:51.146
associated with them.

00:50:51.336 --> 00:50:52.186
But, through this normal

00:50:52.186 --> 00:50:54.016
manipulation, the object will

00:50:54.016 --> 00:50:54.946
seem to have a much more

00:50:54.946 --> 00:50:56.626
smoother and detailed surface,

00:50:56.976 --> 00:50:58.466
without the need to, again, add

00:50:58.466 --> 00:50:59.756
or change any of the geometry

00:50:59.756 --> 00:51:01.036
associated with this mesh.

00:51:02.396 --> 00:51:03.966
Whew. Alright, so we've gone

00:51:03.966 --> 00:51:05.356
through enough about normals.

00:51:05.356 --> 00:51:06.776
Let's, kind of, go over what it

00:51:06.776 --> 00:51:07.846
takes to add a little bit more

00:51:07.846 --> 00:51:09.426
shiny to your scene.

00:51:10.216 --> 00:51:12.066
CampfiAR is definitely starting

00:51:12.066 --> 00:51:12.526
to look better.

00:51:13.076 --> 00:51:14.756
But, some of these normal maps

00:51:14.756 --> 00:51:15.706
[inaudible] but some of these

00:51:15.706 --> 00:51:16.886
parts seem a bit dull,

00:51:17.406 --> 00:51:18.416
especially the objects that you

00:51:18.416 --> 00:51:19.786
expect to be shiny or

00:51:19.786 --> 00:51:20.806
reflective, kind of like the

00:51:20.806 --> 00:51:21.916
kettle or the fish in this

00:51:21.916 --> 00:51:22.136
scene.

00:51:23.286 --> 00:51:24.576
What we see here is the results

00:51:24.576 --> 00:51:26.356
of applying a metal map to our

00:51:26.426 --> 00:51:26.886
AR scene.

00:51:27.496 --> 00:51:29.766
A metal map is used to determine

00:51:29.766 --> 00:51:31.146
which object surfaces should

00:51:31.146 --> 00:51:33.016
exhibit reflective properties.

00:51:33.896 --> 00:51:34.966
Once the material property's

00:51:34.966 --> 00:51:36.756
activated, notice how shiny and

00:51:36.756 --> 00:51:38.326
reflective the area's we've

00:51:38.326 --> 00:51:39.306
designated as being metallic

00:51:39.306 --> 00:51:39.626
are.

00:51:40.096 --> 00:51:41.256
And, on the kettle as well as

00:51:41.406 --> 00:51:42.476
the scales of the fish.

00:51:42.476 --> 00:51:45.956
So, let's focus specifically on

00:51:45.956 --> 00:51:46.276
the kettle.

00:51:47.166 --> 00:51:48.056
We'll begin by taking the

00:51:48.086 --> 00:51:49.796
original albedo map, and then

00:51:49.796 --> 00:51:51.166
apply a metal map to the

00:51:51.166 --> 00:51:52.446
metalness property of this

00:51:52.446 --> 00:51:52.836
material.

00:51:53.756 --> 00:51:55.106
After the application of the

00:51:55.106 --> 00:51:56.706
metal map, the 3D render will

00:51:56.706 --> 00:51:58.006
actually designate the surface

00:51:58.006 --> 00:52:00.466
to be reflective in the areas on

00:52:00.466 --> 00:52:01.446
the map that were actually

00:52:01.446 --> 00:52:01.626
white.

00:52:02.296 --> 00:52:03.316
And, despite begin called

00:52:03.316 --> 00:52:04.326
metalness, it doesn't

00:52:04.326 --> 00:52:05.336
necessarily mean that your

00:52:05.336 --> 00:52:06.886
object needs to contain metal.

00:52:07.556 --> 00:52:08.336
Rather, we're just letting the

00:52:08.336 --> 00:52:10.296
3D engine know that this object

00:52:10.296 --> 00:52:11.416
should exhibit, kind of, a

00:52:11.416 --> 00:52:12.906
reflective surface.

00:52:13.416 --> 00:52:16.016
Now, it's best to use the

00:52:16.016 --> 00:52:17.176
metalness map on your model,

00:52:17.526 --> 00:52:19.336
like our kettle here, when it

00:52:19.336 --> 00:52:21.266
has both a mixture of metallic

00:52:21.266 --> 00:52:22.466
and non-metallic surfaces.

00:52:23.066 --> 00:52:24.276
It's a simple grayscale map,

00:52:24.726 --> 00:52:25.676
where the level of metalness

00:52:25.676 --> 00:52:27.646
ranges from being black, for

00:52:27.646 --> 00:52:29.006
non-metal surfaces, to white,

00:52:29.006 --> 00:52:30.166
for metallic surfaces.

00:52:31.016 --> 00:52:32.256
And, it allows for a single

00:52:32.256 --> 00:52:34.836
material to be used to represent

00:52:34.836 --> 00:52:35.906
both reflective and

00:52:35.906 --> 00:52:37.466
non-reflective surfaces on your

00:52:37.466 --> 00:52:38.126
single object.

00:52:38.926 --> 00:52:41.216
However, this kettle's a bit

00:52:41.276 --> 00:52:42.066
crazy reflective.

00:52:42.336 --> 00:52:43.966
And, doesn't really quite

00:52:44.016 --> 00:52:44.966
provide the look that we're

00:52:44.966 --> 00:52:45.466
hoping for.

00:52:45.846 --> 00:52:47.636
So, in this case, we want to

00:52:47.636 --> 00:52:49.146
potentially vary the amount of

00:52:49.146 --> 00:52:50.456
reflectivity, as well as

00:52:50.456 --> 00:52:51.906
simulate the fact that all

00:52:51.906 --> 00:52:53.576
surfaces are not perfectly

00:52:53.576 --> 00:52:54.006
smooth.

00:52:54.296 --> 00:52:55.526
And, they actually might exhibit

00:52:55.816 --> 00:52:58.056
slight small, microabrasions to

00:52:58.056 --> 00:52:58.696
their surface.

00:52:59.206 --> 00:53:01.466
And, this is where the roughness

00:53:01.466 --> 00:53:02.446
material property comes into

00:53:02.446 --> 00:53:02.736
play.

00:53:04.066 --> 00:53:05.516
So, returning back to CampfiAR,

00:53:06.066 --> 00:53:07.246
you can see how the reflective

00:53:07.246 --> 00:53:08.776
surfaces are a bit too smooth.

00:53:09.266 --> 00:53:10.986
As we layer on the roughness

00:53:10.986 --> 00:53:12.316
maps, you can see that we are

00:53:12.316 --> 00:53:13.746
going to modify both the kettle

00:53:13.746 --> 00:53:15.226
and the fish to adjust the way

00:53:15.226 --> 00:53:16.026
that they're reflecting.

00:53:16.426 --> 00:53:17.816
And then, after we apply the

00:53:17.816 --> 00:53:19.316
roughness material property to

00:53:19.316 --> 00:53:21.116
both of these objects, you can

00:53:21.146 --> 00:53:22.306
clearly see the reduction of the

00:53:22.306 --> 00:53:22.926
reflectivity.

00:53:23.876 --> 00:53:25.066
This combination of roughness

00:53:25.066 --> 00:53:26.516
and metalness properties are

00:53:26.516 --> 00:53:28.486
another important concept to

00:53:28.486 --> 00:53:28.996
focus on.

00:53:29.256 --> 00:53:30.356
So, let's dive a little bit

00:53:30.356 --> 00:53:31.396
deeper into the roughness

00:53:31.436 --> 00:53:34.086
material property.

00:53:34.186 --> 00:53:36.076
Use roughness to simulate micro

00:53:36.076 --> 00:53:38.216
surface details, which in turn

00:53:38.216 --> 00:53:39.686
will affect the way light is

00:53:39.736 --> 00:53:41.216
being bounced off that surface.

00:53:41.846 --> 00:53:43.086
If the roughness property is set

00:53:43.116 --> 00:53:45.236
to completely smooth, then light

00:53:45.236 --> 00:53:46.796
will bounce off of your surface

00:53:46.796 --> 00:53:47.266
like a mirror.

00:53:48.066 --> 00:53:49.196
As you increase the roughness of

00:53:49.196 --> 00:53:50.666
the material, light reflects

00:53:50.666 --> 00:53:52.006
over a wider range of angles.

00:53:52.336 --> 00:53:54.016
Here, we're slowly scaling a

00:53:54.016 --> 00:53:55.816
constant roughness value between

00:53:56.086 --> 00:53:57.956
no roughness to max roughness on

00:53:57.956 --> 00:53:58.786
the kettle itself.

00:53:59.386 --> 00:54:02.326
And, this is a good way of being

00:54:02.326 --> 00:54:04.486
able to simulate the concept of

00:54:04.486 --> 00:54:06.456
having microsurfaces, and

00:54:06.456 --> 00:54:07.606
blurring reflection to the point

00:54:07.606 --> 00:54:09.396
where you might not see any

00:54:09.396 --> 00:54:10.706
reflectivity depending on which

00:54:10.706 --> 00:54:13.106
range you put your value to.

00:54:13.576 --> 00:54:16.536
So, for the kettle, we've taken

00:54:16.536 --> 00:54:17.746
the original metal surface, and

00:54:17.746 --> 00:54:19.416
instead of just applying a

00:54:19.416 --> 00:54:21.476
constant roughness value to it,

00:54:21.876 --> 00:54:23.006
we actually applied a roughness

00:54:23.006 --> 00:54:23.176
map.

00:54:24.086 --> 00:54:25.436
And, this will help designate

00:54:25.706 --> 00:54:27.146
the surfaces where we will be

00:54:27.146 --> 00:54:29.656
scattering the light more often,

00:54:29.656 --> 00:54:30.786
and more than others.

00:54:31.476 --> 00:54:32.956
Once we've applied the roughness

00:54:32.956 --> 00:54:34.926
map, we get to see the real

00:54:34.926 --> 00:54:36.346
final look of the reflectiveness

00:54:36.346 --> 00:54:37.346
of this kettle, which is a lot

00:54:37.346 --> 00:54:38.906
less shiny as before.

00:54:40.106 --> 00:54:42.406
Now, a combination of this

00:54:42.486 --> 00:54:43.826
metalness property and this

00:54:43.826 --> 00:54:45.586
roughness property really make

00:54:45.586 --> 00:54:46.976
your reflective AR models look

00:54:46.976 --> 00:54:47.566
phenomenal.

00:54:48.486 --> 00:54:49.656
Roughness can be used to tweak

00:54:49.656 --> 00:54:50.926
how much of your objects will

00:54:50.926 --> 00:54:51.756
reflect the environment.

00:54:52.046 --> 00:54:53.586
And, can really be used to add a

00:54:53.586 --> 00:54:54.636
lot more realism to your

00:54:54.636 --> 00:54:55.626
metallic surfaces.

00:54:56.296 --> 00:54:57.706
You can use this roughness map

00:54:57.826 --> 00:55:00.076
to add additional minor details

00:55:00.076 --> 00:55:01.436
as we've done here, to make our

00:55:01.436 --> 00:55:02.366
kettle look a little more

00:55:02.366 --> 00:55:02.946
scuffed up.

00:55:04.066 --> 00:55:05.726
Now, to close out materials, we

00:55:05.726 --> 00:55:06.316
have two more material

00:55:06.316 --> 00:55:07.356
properties that I want to

00:55:07.356 --> 00:55:09.256
discuss to further refine your

00:55:09.256 --> 00:55:11.546
models, and have a good balance

00:55:11.546 --> 00:55:12.646
between performance and

00:55:12.646 --> 00:55:13.276
aesthetics.

00:55:14.796 --> 00:55:16.416
Ambient occlusion is a material

00:55:16.416 --> 00:55:17.686
property that is used to provide

00:55:17.686 --> 00:55:20.216
your model with self-shadowing,

00:55:20.216 --> 00:55:21.476
which in turn can lead to adding

00:55:21.476 --> 00:55:23.016
additional depth and details to

00:55:23.016 --> 00:55:23.856
your AR models.

00:55:24.416 --> 00:55:27.026
Now, while normal maps are great

00:55:27.286 --> 00:55:28.296
for applying significant amount

00:55:28.296 --> 00:55:30.486
of details back into your AR

00:55:30.636 --> 00:55:32.296
model, you can use ambient

00:55:32.296 --> 00:55:33.946
occlusion to really hammer in

00:55:34.096 --> 00:55:34.796
those details.

00:55:35.336 --> 00:55:36.386
Here, we're visualizing the

00:55:36.386 --> 00:55:37.496
ambient occlusion maps for

00:55:37.646 --> 00:55:39.786
CampfiAR, and it's a bit of a

00:55:39.786 --> 00:55:41.036
difficult effect to demonstrate,

00:55:41.036 --> 00:55:42.246
as it's meant to be relatively

00:55:42.246 --> 00:55:42.616
subtle.

00:55:42.616 --> 00:55:44.226
But, see if you can notice the

00:55:44.226 --> 00:55:45.806
additional shadows on the logs,

00:55:45.896 --> 00:55:47.086
as well as certain areas near

00:55:47.086 --> 00:55:48.006
the bottom of the kettle.

00:55:48.826 --> 00:55:50.336
In our case here, it's kind of

00:55:50.336 --> 00:55:51.456
like playing Where's Waldo?

00:55:51.456 --> 00:55:53.356
with shadows, so let's focus in

00:55:53.356 --> 00:55:56.876
on the logs in the scene.

00:55:57.086 --> 00:55:58.726
So, here we're showing you the

00:55:58.726 --> 00:56:00.686
normal maped logs before.

00:56:00.836 --> 00:56:02.436
Now, there's some great details

00:56:02.436 --> 00:56:03.756
found in the ridges, but we can

00:56:03.756 --> 00:56:04.746
definitely improve some of these

00:56:04.746 --> 00:56:05.256
areas.

00:56:06.366 --> 00:56:07.436
Now, as we look at the ambient

00:56:07.436 --> 00:56:08.626
occlusion map, you can see how

00:56:08.626 --> 00:56:10.366
we've added some regions of

00:56:10.696 --> 00:56:11.386
self-shadowing.

00:56:11.386 --> 00:56:12.956
So, lower portions of the log,

00:56:12.956 --> 00:56:14.176
as well as around the small

00:56:14.176 --> 00:56:15.026
embedded stumps.

00:56:15.346 --> 00:56:17.746
And, after we apply the map to

00:56:17.746 --> 00:56:19.196
our ambient occlusion property,

00:56:19.446 --> 00:56:20.746
I hope you can see the benefits

00:56:20.746 --> 00:56:22.286
of adding those baked detail

00:56:22.286 --> 00:56:24.036
shadows without the need of

00:56:24.036 --> 00:56:25.516
using expensive dynamic lights

00:56:25.516 --> 00:56:26.066
in your scene.

00:56:26.586 --> 00:56:30.266
When working in AR, we recommend

00:56:30.266 --> 00:56:31.426
that you actually bake your

00:56:31.426 --> 00:56:32.766
ambient occlusion into a map.

00:56:33.316 --> 00:56:34.086
Which is what we've done for

00:56:34.086 --> 00:56:34.456
CampfiAR.

00:56:34.456 --> 00:56:36.426
Rather than use the alternative,

00:56:37.086 --> 00:56:39.056
such as screen space ambient

00:56:39.326 --> 00:56:40.306
occlusions, which is a

00:56:40.306 --> 00:56:41.886
camera-based post-process

00:56:41.886 --> 00:56:43.286
effect, and can potentially lead

00:56:43.286 --> 00:56:45.256
to poor rendering performance in

00:56:45.706 --> 00:56:47.076
your scene.

00:56:47.176 --> 00:56:48.336
And, last but certainly not

00:56:48.336 --> 00:56:50.686
least, be frugal with the use of

00:56:50.686 --> 00:56:51.526
your transparency in your

00:56:51.526 --> 00:56:52.346
materials materials.

00:56:52.346 --> 00:56:53.926
If you must use transparencies,

00:56:54.126 --> 00:56:54.956
we recommend that you use

00:56:54.956 --> 00:56:56.336
separate materials for objects

00:56:56.336 --> 00:56:57.506
where you see a combination of

00:56:57.716 --> 00:56:59.066
transparent and non-transparent

00:56:59.066 --> 00:56:59.696
surfaces.

00:57:00.956 --> 00:57:02.356
In general, when working with AR

00:57:02.356 --> 00:57:04.256
content, the use of a lot of

00:57:04.256 --> 00:57:05.216
transparent surfaces can

00:57:05.216 --> 00:57:07.376
potentially have a huge impact

00:57:07.376 --> 00:57:09.106
on performance, especially if

00:57:09.106 --> 00:57:10.206
you are having transparent

00:57:10.206 --> 00:57:11.036
surfaces that are, kind of,

00:57:11.036 --> 00:57:12.526
stacked in front of each other

00:57:12.606 --> 00:57:13.286
when you're viewing them.

00:57:13.716 --> 00:57:14.726
This is known as overdraw, and

00:57:14.726 --> 00:57:15.196
it's something that you

00:57:15.196 --> 00:57:16.526
definitely want to avoid when

00:57:16.526 --> 00:57:17.306
you're working in AR.

