go through.

00:57:23.036 --> 00:57:24.646
So far, we've focused mostly on

00:57:25.126 --> 00:57:27.156
how the AR content will react to

00:57:27.266 --> 00:57:28.786
the simulated spotlights found

00:57:28.786 --> 00:57:29.826
in our 3D engines.

00:57:30.156 --> 00:57:31.276
But now, it's time to focus on

00:57:31.276 --> 00:57:32.576
some ways to make our content

00:57:32.576 --> 00:57:33.966
seem like it's actually part of

00:57:33.966 --> 00:57:34.506
the real world.

00:57:35.046 --> 00:57:37.696
A fantastic option to use to

00:57:37.696 --> 00:57:38.846
compensate for varied lighting

00:57:38.846 --> 00:57:40.226
conditions is to leverage one of

00:57:40.306 --> 00:57:44.636
ARKit's well known features, and

00:57:44.636 --> 00:57:45.326
light estimation.

00:57:45.996 --> 00:57:47.116
Let's begin by activating this

00:57:47.116 --> 00:57:48.126
functionality and see how it

00:57:48.126 --> 00:57:48.736
affects our kettle.

00:57:49.156 --> 00:57:50.286
Notice that how when the ambient

00:57:50.286 --> 00:57:51.406
light changes in intensity in

00:57:51.406 --> 00:57:52.906
the real world, a similar

00:57:52.906 --> 00:57:53.766
adjustment is made to the

00:57:53.766 --> 00:57:55.316
ambient light in our AR scene.

00:57:56.436 --> 00:57:57.676
The way this works is that ARKit

00:57:57.676 --> 00:57:59.256
analyzes each frame of the

00:57:59.256 --> 00:58:01.286
video, and uses them to estimate

00:58:01.286 --> 00:58:02.306
the lighting condition of the

00:58:02.306 --> 00:58:02.936
real world.

00:58:02.936 --> 00:58:05.076
It is an absolutely magical

00:58:05.076 --> 00:58:06.756
feature that helps assure that

00:58:06.756 --> 00:58:08.136
the amount to light applied to

00:58:08.136 --> 00:58:09.776
your AR content matches what you

00:58:09.776 --> 00:58:10.546
see in the real world.

00:58:10.546 --> 00:58:13.536
Now, that we have magical light

00:58:13.536 --> 00:58:15.026
wizards living in our AR scene,

00:58:15.096 --> 00:58:16.086
let's discuss shadows.

00:58:16.796 --> 00:58:18.756
Shadows in AR are really, really

00:58:18.756 --> 00:58:19.416
hard to get right.

00:58:20.246 --> 00:58:21.176
Your shadow needs to be able to

00:58:21.176 --> 00:58:22.506
work in a wide variety of

00:58:22.506 --> 00:58:23.206
situations.

00:58:23.386 --> 00:58:25.096
Remember that people can be

00:58:25.096 --> 00:58:26.206
potentially using your app

00:58:26.356 --> 00:58:26.776
anywhere.

00:58:27.046 --> 00:58:28.516
And, if your AR shadows differ

00:58:28.916 --> 00:58:29.766
from the ones that are seen in

00:58:29.766 --> 00:58:30.796
the real world environment, it

00:58:30.796 --> 00:58:31.976
can be relatively jarring for

00:58:31.976 --> 00:58:32.676
your experience.

00:58:34.016 --> 00:58:35.136
Here, we have tried to

00:58:35.226 --> 00:58:36.936
incorrectly cast a dynamic

00:58:36.936 --> 00:58:39.396
shadow by using a directional

00:58:39.396 --> 00:58:40.996
light as a sharp angle in our 3D

00:58:40.996 --> 00:58:41.286
engine.

00:58:42.226 --> 00:58:43.686
Shadows are a great way to make

00:58:43.686 --> 00:58:44.866
objects actually feel grounded

00:58:44.866 --> 00:58:45.716
in the real world, but in this

00:58:45.716 --> 00:58:47.066
case, it doesn't really match

00:58:47.066 --> 00:58:48.256
the shadows being seen in the

00:58:48.256 --> 00:58:49.156
surrounding environment.

00:58:49.626 --> 00:58:50.716
It's like we're purposely trying

00:58:50.716 --> 00:58:52.046
to defy the laws of physics

00:58:53.816 --> 00:58:53.926
here.

00:58:54.136 --> 00:58:55.316
Instead, we suggest that you

00:58:55.316 --> 00:58:56.326
place your directional light

00:58:56.326 --> 00:58:58.076
directly overhead, and play a

00:58:58.076 --> 00:58:58.846
little bit around with the

00:58:58.846 --> 00:59:00.526
intensity of that effect to make

00:59:00.526 --> 00:59:02.536
sure that it actually feels a

00:59:02.536 --> 00:59:03.476
little bit more subtle.

00:59:04.236 --> 00:59:05.136
This will allow your shadows to

00:59:05.136 --> 00:59:06.216
work in a lot more different

00:59:06.216 --> 00:59:08.016
situations, and a lot more

00:59:08.016 --> 00:59:08.786
different scenarios.

00:59:09.606 --> 00:59:10.926
An alternative to this is

00:59:10.926 --> 00:59:12.076
actually using a method where

00:59:12.076 --> 00:59:13.186
you can create your own drop

00:59:13.186 --> 00:59:14.356
shadow, rather than using

00:59:14.356 --> 00:59:15.576
dynamic lights in your scene,

00:59:16.016 --> 00:59:17.556
which can get expensive, and can

00:59:17.556 --> 00:59:19.446
severely affect performance if

00:59:19.446 --> 00:59:20.516
you're rendering a lot of 3D

00:59:20.516 --> 00:59:20.966
content.

00:59:21.736 --> 00:59:23.956
Take the time to craft those

00:59:24.296 --> 00:59:25.256
really good shadows.

00:59:25.256 --> 00:59:26.746
And ensure that they will fit in

00:59:26.746 --> 00:59:28.736
as many real world situations as

00:59:28.796 --> 00:59:29.166
possible.

00:59:29.746 --> 00:59:32.306
Ah, environment maps.

00:59:33.086 --> 00:59:34.486
If you really want to astound

00:59:34.486 --> 00:59:35.866
people, you definitely want to

00:59:35.866 --> 00:59:37.326
use these maps, especially on

00:59:37.326 --> 00:59:39.166
those AR objects that exhibit

00:59:39.166 --> 00:59:39.886
reflectivity.

00:59:40.796 --> 00:59:41.946
It'll make it seem like your AR

00:59:41.946 --> 00:59:43.746
content exists right here, in

00:59:43.746 --> 00:59:44.366
the real world.

00:59:44.836 --> 00:59:46.336
And, to make it super easy to

00:59:46.336 --> 00:59:48.086
leverage their powers we want to

00:59:48.086 --> 00:59:49.606
show you how one of the new

00:59:49.606 --> 00:59:52.176
features in iOS 12 and ARKit

00:59:52.176 --> 00:59:54.006
2.0, automatic environmental

00:59:54.006 --> 00:59:55.586
mapping, can help you achieve

00:59:55.586 --> 00:59:56.026
this effect.

00:59:57.576 --> 00:59:58.826
If you take a close look at the

00:59:58.826 --> 01:00:00.306
kettle, originally we're using a

01:00:00.306 --> 01:00:01.726
baked environment map that has a

01:00:01.816 --> 01:00:02.976
kind of blush tinge to it.

01:00:04.396 --> 01:00:05.246
Once we've activated the

01:00:05.246 --> 01:00:06.836
automatic environmental mapping,

01:00:07.076 --> 01:00:07.996
notice how the kettle now

01:00:07.996 --> 01:00:09.216
reflects a lot of the ground,

01:00:09.286 --> 01:00:10.706
and the surrounding color of the

01:00:10.706 --> 01:00:11.786
current environment that we're

01:00:11.786 --> 01:00:11.986
in.

