You can even see a little bit of

01:00:13.856 --> 01:00:15.656
the green from the grass that

01:00:15.656 --> 01:00:16.496
this kettle's sitting in.

01:00:17.166 --> 01:00:18.896
This is a fantastic feature

01:00:19.176 --> 01:00:20.486
that'll really help ground your

01:00:20.486 --> 01:00:22.266
objects into the real world, and

01:00:22.266 --> 01:00:23.616
with careful use of roughness,

01:00:24.156 --> 01:00:25.126
can really enhance the

01:00:25.126 --> 01:00:26.736
believability of your scene.

01:00:28.536 --> 01:00:30.346
So, now why is automatic

01:00:30.346 --> 01:00:31.846
environmental mapping so

01:00:31.846 --> 01:00:32.976
actually incredible?

01:00:33.436 --> 01:00:35.516
Typically, these maps are used

01:00:35.516 --> 01:00:37.036
to simulate the ability of

01:00:37.076 --> 01:00:39.116
metallic surfaces to mirror the

01:00:39.116 --> 01:00:40.056
environment around them.

01:00:41.106 --> 01:00:43.156
You can see example of a cube

01:00:43.156 --> 01:00:44.006
environment map here.

01:00:45.266 --> 01:00:46.426
Now, before ARKit added

01:00:46.426 --> 01:00:47.846
automatic environmental mapping,

01:00:47.946 --> 01:00:48.886
you had to provide your own

01:00:48.886 --> 01:00:50.086
image, and hope that it was

01:00:50.086 --> 01:00:51.146
generic enough to work in a

01:00:51.146 --> 01:00:52.936
large variety of situations that

01:00:52.936 --> 01:00:54.046
your app may be used in.

01:00:54.586 --> 01:00:56.986
But now, with ARKit 2.0, you can

01:00:56.986 --> 01:00:58.006
kiss those sleepless night,

01:00:58.006 --> 01:00:59.176
fretting about whether your

01:00:59.176 --> 01:01:00.356
environment map is actually

01:01:00.356 --> 01:01:01.516
ruining your AR experience.

